        "score": 0.49344587,
        "text": "The document discusses the increase in uplift costs for electricity in 2021, which rose to $5.34 per MWh from $0.94 per MWh in 2020. The total uplift costs in 2021 were approximately $2.1 billion, significantly higher than the $359 million in 2020. The main contributor to this increase was the ancillary service imbalance settlement. Other significant components included the ERCOT system administrative fee ($218 million or $0.55 per MWh) and Emergency Response Service (ERS) program costs ($35 million or $0.09 per MWh). The real-time revenue neutrality allocation (RENA) decreased dramatically to less than $1 million in 2021, attributed to high negative RENA during Winter Storm Uri.\n\nA graph (Figure 5) illustrates the all-in electricity costs in 2021, highlighting the impact of Winter Storm Uri. Ancillary services costs, excluding the storm period, would have been $6.00 per MWh in 2021, up from $1.00 per MWh in 2020. This increase was driven by high ancillary services prices following the storm and additional services purchased by ERCOT later in the year. Uplift costs, excluding the storm, would have been $0.91 per MWh, similar to 2020 levels.",
