        "text": "The document discusses the correlation between gas prices and energy prices in a competitive market, highlighting that fuel costs are a major component of production costs for generators. In 2023, this correlation was not evident due to ERCOT's ECRS implementation, which limited price reductions. Key points include:\n\n- Ancillary service costs increased by 28.1% to $4.21 per MWh in 2023.\n- Uplift costs rose to $0.90 per MWh, totaling nearly $400 million, a 16.5% increase from 2022, mainly due to the Real-Time Revenue Neutrality Allocation (RENA).\n- The largest uplift costs were the ERCOT System Administrative Fee and Emergency Response Service program costs.\n\nA graph (Figure 3) shows the variation in real-time energy prices by time of day from May to September 2023, indicating higher prices in the afternoon and evening compared to 2022.",
