        "score": 0.41327435,
        "text": "The document page discusses the breakdown of electricity costs in 2022 within the ERCOT market. Key points include:\n\n- Ancillary services costs were $3.29 per MWh, a 90% reduction from 2021 but more than triple the 2020 costs.\n- Uplift costs were $0.77 per MWh, significantly lower than $5.34 in 2021 and $0.94 in 2020.\n- Total uplift costs in 2022 were approximately $368 million, down from $2.1 billion in 2021, largely due to the absence of events like Winter Storm Uri.\n- Major components of uplift costs included the ERCOT System Administrative Fee ($293 million) and Emergency Response Service program costs ($36 million).\n- Real-Time Revenue Neutrality Allocation (RENA) was $43 million, a significant increase from less than $1 million in 2021.\n- A graph illustrates monthly variations in all-in electricity costs, showing peaks in summer months, with natural gas prices also charted.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/ERCOT/report/2022/page_41.jpg",
          "page_num": 41,
          "title": "State of the Market Report for the ERCOT Electricity Markets",
          "year": 2022,
          "market": "ERCOT",
          "data_type": "report"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "4b20eb39-e298-467a-924a-2f258772ef52",
        "score": 0.40872815,
        "text": "The document discusses real-time transmission congestion and congested areas, focusing on their economic value. Congestion is evaluated by multiplying the shadow price of each constraint by the flow over it, with the shadow price representing the marginal cost of redispatch needed to manage the constraint. A congested area is defined by consolidating multiple constraints based on geographic proximity and direction.\n\nFigure 34 illustrates the ten most costly real-time congested areas, measured by congestion value. In 2022, there were 536 unique constraints with a median financial impact of $469,000, compared to 526 constraints in 2021 with a median impact of $310,000. The West Texas Export GTC had the highest congestion value in 2022 at $304 million, mainly due to transmission maintenance outages and high renewable output. The Panhandle GTC, which had the highest value in 2021, dropped to seventh in 2022 due to resolved maintenance outages.\n\nSpecific constraints, such as those on the Jewet to Singleton 345 kV Lines and others, were primarily due to new transmission structures and planned outages.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/ERCOT/report/2022/page_88.jpg",
          "page_num": 88,
          "title": "State of the Market Report for the ERCOT Electricity Markets",
          "year": 2022,
          "market": "ERCOT",
          "data_type": "report"
