      {
        "id": "28d23102-ded8-4b4e-b865-7b73bcc12c2a",
        "score": 0.39460063,
        "text": "The document discusses transmission congestion and Congestion Revenue Rights (CRRs) within the Electric Reliability Council of Texas (ERCOT) system. It highlights areas identified in the 2021 Long-Term System Assessment (LTSA) report, focusing on day-ahead congestion costs, which were highest on three main paths. These costs amounted to approximately $1,380 million, less than the $2,050 million in the real-time market, reflecting differences between expected and actual outcomes, particularly due to Winter Storm Uri and wind generation scheduling.\n\nThe section on \"Irresolvable Constraints\" explains the shadow price of a constraint, which is the marginal cost of managing it. ERCOT caps shadow prices to prevent unreasonable costs when constraints cannot be resolved. The shadow price caps for 2021 were:\n\n- $9,251 per MW for base-case constraints or voltage violations.\n- $4,500 per MW for 345 kV constraints.\n- $3,500 per MW for 138 kV constraints.\n- $2,800 per MW for 69 kV thermal violations.\n\nGeneral Transmission Constraints (GTCs) are considered base-case stability constraints with a shadow price cap of $9,251 per MW. Violated constraints occurred in 10% of intervals in 2021, up from 8% in 2020.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/ERCOT/report/2021/page_94.jpg",
          "page_num": 94,
          "title": "State of the Market Report for the ERCOT Electricity Markets",
          "year": 2021,
          "market": "ERCOT",
          "data_type": "report"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "5cc94121-69b8-4bec-ace6-d5f100e7accd",
        "score": 0.394532,
        "text": "The document page discusses transmission congestion and CRRs (Congestion Revenue Rights) for 2021. It reports 526 unique constraints with a median financial impact of $310,000, compared to 450 constraints in 2020 with a median impact of $222,000. Figure 42 illustrates the ten most costly real-time constraints by congestion value.\n\nThe Panhandle GTC constraint had the highest congestion value in 2021 at $129 million, primarily due to high intermittent resources and planned transmission outages, including ETT maintenance. This was about 10% lower than the $139 million cost in 2020.\n\nSpecific constraints like Pawnee to Calaveras, Fayette Plant to Winchester, and Carmichael Bend to Decordova Dam were affected by Winter Storm Uri. Other constraints were due to planned outages or output from inverter-based resources.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/ERCOT/report/2021/page_93.jpg",
          "page_num": 93,
          "title": "State of the Market Report for the ERCOT Electricity Markets",
          "year": 2021,
          "market": "ERCOT",
          "data_type": "report"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "6c43b366-fbb7-4772-b804-9e309dd6dd4e",
        "score": 0.38651222,
        "text": "The document discusses the increase in uplift costs for electricity in 2021, which rose to $5.34 per MWh from $0.94 per MWh in 2020. The total uplift costs in 2021 were approximately $2.1 billion, significantly higher than the $359 million in 2020. The main contributor to this increase was the ancillary service imbalance settlement. Other significant components included the ERCOT system administrative fee ($218 million or $0.55 per MWh) and Emergency Response Service (ERS) program costs ($35 million or $0.09 per MWh). The real-time revenue neutrality allocation (RENA) decreased dramatically to less than $1 million in 2021, attributed to high negative RENA during Winter Storm Uri.\n\nA graph (Figure 5) illustrates the all-in electricity costs in 2021, highlighting the impact of Winter Storm Uri. Ancillary services costs, excluding the storm period, would have been $6.00 per MWh in 2021, up from $1.00 per MWh in 2020. This increase was driven by high ancillary services prices following the storm and additional services purchased by ERCOT later in the year. Uplift costs, excluding the storm, would have been $0.91 per MWh, similar to 2020 levels.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/ERCOT/report/2021/page_41.jpg",
          "page_num": 41,
          "title": "State of the Market Report for the ERCOT Electricity Markets",
          "year": 2021,
          "market": "ERCOT",
          "data_type": "report"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "dc24aefd-501b-4d9b-929e-303d2da20855",
        "score": 0.38488135,
        "text": "The document discusses real-time constraints and congested areas in the electricity market for 2021. It highlights three major Grid Transmission Constraints (GTCs): Panhandle, West Texas Export, and North Edinburg Lobo, which were among the top ten congested areas, with congestion costs rising to $410 million from $190 million in 2020. Despite planned upgrades, congestion persisted due to renewable energy output. ERCOT is actively working on solutions through workshops and taskforces. The top ten most congested areas incurred costs of $820 million, while the most frequently constrained areas totaled $566 million. Additionally, 14 element combinations were identified as irresolvable constraints, with shadow price caps applied as per methodology.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/ERCOT/report/2021/page_195.jpg",
          "page_num": 195,
          "title": "State of the Market Report for the ERCOT Electricity Markets",
