      },
      {
        "id": "7874e0da-69a6-4e61-9e77-e476b4f80095",
        "score": 0.38211444,
        "text": "The document provides an analysis of 2021 prices and outcomes in ERCOT's real-time energy market. It includes a table (Table A1) summarizing the annual aggregate costs of various ERCOT charges or payments for 2021, categorized by cost type. The major costs listed are:\n\n- Energy: $65,946 million\n- Regulation Up: $869 million\n- Regulation Down: $348 million\n- Responsive Reserve: $8,232 million\n- Non-Spin: $2,176 million\n- CRR Auction Distribution: $831 million\n- Balancing Account Surplus: $111 million\n- CRR DAM Payment: $1,289 million\n- PTP DAM Charge: $1,113 million\n- PTP RT Payment: $1,563 million\n- Emergency Response Service: $59 million\n- Revenue Neutrality: $1 million\n- ERCOT Fee: $218 million\n- Other Load Allocation: $1,831 million\n\nThe section also discusses real-time market prices, noting that they vary significantly by time of day. It mentions that Figure A1 (not shown) illustrates the load-weighted average real-time prices for peak and off-peak categories for each month in 2021. Peak hours are defined as hour ending (HE) 7 to HE 22 on weekdays, while off-peak includes all other hours. These categories align with those traded in forward markets.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/ERCOT/report/2021/page_157.jpg",
          "page_num": 157,
          "title": "State of the Market Report for the ERCOT Electricity Markets",
          "year": 2021,
          "market": "ERCOT",
          "data_type": "report"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "46cab434-b6dc-4e63-acdd-0e330a894cb9",
        "score": 0.3808968,
        "text": "The document page is from the \"2022 State of the Market Report\" and focuses on transmission congestion and Congestion Revenue Rights (CRRs). It discusses pricing for base-case and voltage violations, with specific rates for different kV levels. General Transmission Constraints (GTCs) have a shadow price cap of $5,251 per MW.\n\nTable A4 lists \"Irresolvable Elements,\" detailing various contingency codes, elements, shadow prices, effective and termination dates, load zones, and the number of binding intervals in 2022. Key points include:\n\n- The Valley Import GTC has a high equivalent max shadow price of $9,251 per MWh.\n- Several elements have a max shadow price of $3,500 per MWh, with adjusted prices for 2022.\n- Four constraints were resolved and removed from the list after ERCOT's annual review.\n- Only one West zone irresolvable constraint remained after the termination of four others.\n- New constraints were identified in 2022, including one in the South zone and one in the North zone.",
        "metadata": {
          "drive_path": "gs://tumeai-rag/ERCOT/report/2022/page_182.jpg",
          "page_num": 182,
          "title": "State of the Market Report for the ERCOT Electricity Markets",
          "year": 2022,
          "market": "ERCOT",
          "data_type": "report"
        }
      },
      {
        "id": "62665f61-9424-4365-9653-795acec74a55",
        "score": 0.37921792,
        "text": "The document page discusses transmission congestion and constraints in the energy market. It highlights that the top ten most congested real-time constraints were valued at $928 million, while the most frequently constrained ones totaled $711 million.\n\n**Individual GTCs (Generic Transmission Constraints):**\n- Table A4 lists individual GTCs, their effective dates, and the number of binding hours in 2022 and 2023. For example, the \"North to Houston\" constraint has been effective since December 1, 2010, with 54.4 binding hours in 2022 and 23.4 in 2023.\n\n**Irresolvable Constraints:**\n- Thirteen element combinations were deemed irresolvable in 2023, leading to shadow price caps. These caps are based on a specific methodology to reflect reduced reliability when constraints are irresolvable.\n- Shadow price caps are set at $5,251 per MW for base-case violations, $4,500 per MW for 345 kV constraints, $3,500 per MW for 138 kV, and $2,800 per MW for 69 kV thermal constraints.",
        "metadata": {
